<h2 id="heading-0">The Bookkeeping Pricing Mystery</h2>

<p>Every Texas business owner I've worked with asks the same question: "How much should bookkeeping really cost?" The answer isn't simple, but it's not as complicated as most accountants make it seem.</p>

<p>After helping hundreds of Texas businesses with their books, I've seen patterns. Small service businesses pay too much. Growing companies get nickel-and-dimed with "add-on" fees. And everyone wonders why their CPA firm charges $500/month when they only talk to them quarterly.</p>

<p>Let's break down the real costs and show you how to calculate what you should pay.</p>

<h2 id="heading-1">The Three Pricing Models (And Why Two Are Broken)</h2>

<h3 id="heading-2">1. Hourly Billing: The "Time Trap"</h3>

<p>Most traditional accounting firms charge $150-300/hour. Sounds reasonable until you realize:</p>

<ul>
<li>Simple data entry takes 15-30 minutes but gets billed as a full hour</li>
<li>Questions about reports cost $75-150 each</li>
<li>Year-end adjustments can run $1,000+ in "review time"</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Real Cost:</strong> A basic monthly bookkeeping cycle (bank reconciliation, bills, invoices) costs $800-1,500/month. That's $9,600-18,000/year for work that should cost $2,400-4,800.</p>

<h3 id="heading-3">2. Fixed Monthly: The "Hidden Fees" Model</h3>

<p>Some firms offer "fixed" pricing starting at $500/month, but watch for these add-ons:</p>

<ul>
<li>$50/month for "software access"</li>
<li>$100/month for "unlimited support" (that isn't unlimited)</li>
<li>$200/month for "year-end services" (that should be included)</li>
<li>$150/month for "tax planning" (that happens once a year)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Real Cost:</strong> What starts as $500/month often becomes $900-1,200/month within 6 months.</p>

<h3 id="heading-4">3. Outsourced Flat Rate: The Smart Choice</h3>

<p>Modern bookkeeping services charge a flat monthly fee based on your transaction volume, not hours worked. No surprises, no add-ons, no time traps.</p>

<p><strong>How it works:</strong> You pay based on the number of transactions you process monthly, not the time spent processing them.</p>

