<h2 id="heading-7">Why Texas Businesses Pay Too Much</h2>

<h3 id="heading-8">The "Full Service" Myth</h3>

<p>Most CPA firms sell "full service" packages that include:</p>

<ul>
<li>Bookkeeping (what you need monthly)</li>
<li>Tax planning (happens once a year)</li>
<li>Tax preparation (happens once a year)</li>
<li>Audit defense (happens if you get audited)</li>
<li>Business consulting (what they charge extra for)</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>The problem:</strong> You're paying for services you don't need every month.</p>

<h3 id="heading-9">The "Relationship" Premium</h3>

<p>Local CPA firms charge more because:</p>

<ul>
<li>They have office overhead</li>
<li>They want to build "relationships"</li>
<li>They can charge what the market bears</li>
</ul>

<p>But relationships don't make your books more accurate or your taxes lower.</p>

<h3 id="heading-10">The "Insurance" Factor</h3>

<p>Traditional firms charge premium rates because they carry malpractice insurance and want to cover worst-case scenarios. But most bookkeeping errors are simple data entry mistakes that any trained professional can fix.</p>

<h2 id="heading-11">What You Get for the Money</h2>

<p>When you pay $300-600/month for modern bookkeeping, you should get:</p>

<ul>
<li>Monthly bank and credit card reconciliation</li>
<li>Accurate profit & loss statements</li>
<li>Balance sheet reconciliation</li>
<li>Accounts receivable and payable tracking</li>
<li>Monthly financial reports you can understand</li>
<li>Quarterly tax planning reviews</li>
<li>Year-end tax preparation coordination</li>
<li>Unlimited email and chat support</li>
<li>Direct access to your books (no "portal fees")</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>What you shouldn't pay extra for:</strong> Software subscriptions, data imports, basic reports, or simple questions.</p>

<h2 id="heading-12">The Hidden Costs of Cheap Bookkeeping</h2>

<p>Some businesses try to save money by doing it themselves or using "cheap" services. Here's what that costs:</p>

<h3 id="heading-13">DIY Bookkeeping Costs</h3>

<ul>
<li><strong>Your time:</strong> 4-8 hours/month at $50-100/hour = $200-800/month</li>
<li><strong>Software:</strong> QuickBooks Online = $30/month</li>
<li><strong>Errors:</strong> Overpayments, missed deductions, IRS penalties</li>
<li><strong>Stress:</strong> Priceless (but real)</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-14">"Cheap" Service Problems</h3>

<ul>
<li>Turnover: New bookkeeper every 3-6 months</li>
<li>Errors: Inexperienced staff makes mistakes</li>
<li>Delays: Slow response times</li>
<li>Hidden fees: "Setup fees," "training fees," "software fees"</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="heading-15">How to Choose the Right Bookkeeper</h2>

<h3 id="heading-16">Questions to Ask</h3>

<ul>
<li>"What's your transaction-based pricing?"</li>
<li>"Do you charge for software access or basic questions?"</li>
<li>"How long have your bookkeepers stayed with you?"</li>
<li>"Can I see examples of your financial reports?"</li>
<li>"What's your process for handling errors?"</li>
</ul>

<h3 id="heading-17">Red Flags to Watch For</h3>

<ul>
<li>Hourly billing only</li>
<li>Requires you to use their software</li>
<li>Charges for "basic" services</li>
<li>No contract or money-back guarantee</li>
<li>Can't explain their pricing clearly</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="heading-18">The Bottom Line</h2>

<p>Good bookkeeping shouldn't cost more than 1-2% of your annual revenue. For most Texas businesses, that's $300-600/month.</p>

<p>If you're paying more than that, you're likely overpaying for services you don't need or getting billed for inefficiencies in their process.</p>

<p>The right bookkeeper becomes invisible - your books are always accurate, your reports are always ready, and you never worry about your finances.</p>

<p>That's peace of mind worth paying for, but not at any price.</p>